"Stark A., Huebschmann S., Sellin M., Kralisch D., Trotzki R., Ondruschka B.","Microwave-assisted Kolbe-Schmitt synthesis using ionic liquids or dimcarb as reactive solvents",2009,"Chemical Engineering and Technology","32","11",,"1730","1738",,,10.1002/ceat.200900331,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70350639124&partnerID=40&md5=91ff431a50a22988e5caa07c07078891","Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany","Stark, A., Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany; Huebschmann, S., Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany; Sellin, M., Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany; Kralisch, D., Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany; Trotzki, R., Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany; Ondruschka, B., Institute for Technical Chemistry and Environmental Chemistry, Friedrich-Schiller University, Jena, Germany","The activation of relatively inert carbon dioxide as a building block for organic products is of interest from both ecological and chemical points of view. One of the few industrially relevant processes using CO2 is the Kolbe-Schmitt synthesis. Two strategies to obtain the carboxylated product 2,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid from resorcinol are presented: both Dimcarb and hydrogencarbonate- or methylcarbonate-based ionic liquids are employed as reactive solvents in a microwave-assisted reaction. Reaction optimization shows that the ionic liquids are more reactive than Dimcarb. However, Dimcarb offers advantages with regard to ecological aspects, such as the Global Warming and Human Toxicity Potential and the Cumulative Energy Demand, which were assessed as part of the process development. © 2009 WILEY-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA, Weinheim.","Carbon dioxide; Fine chemicals; Solvents; Sustainable development; Synthesis","Building blockes; Chemical point; Cumulative energy demands; Dihydroxybenzoic acids; DIMCARB; Ecological aspects; Fine chemicals; Human toxicity potentials; Microwave-assisted; Microwave-assisted reactions; Organic products; Process development; Reaction optimization; Reactive solvent; Synthesis; Carbon dioxide; Dyes; Energy management; Global warming; Ionization of liquids; Ions; Microwaves; Phenols; Solvents; Strategic planning; Sustainable development; Ionic liquids",,,,,,"Behr, A., (1985) Chem. Ing. Tech, 57, p. 893; Kolbe, H., (1874) J. Prakt. Chem, 10, p. 89; Schmitt, R., (1885) J. Prakt. Chem, 31, p. 397; Schmitt, R., (1884) German Patent DE, p. 29939; von Heyden, F.W., (1884) German Patent DE, p. 38742; (1893) Marasse, German Patent DE, p. 73279; Lindsey, A.S., Jeskey, H., (1957) Chem. Rev, 57, p. 583; (1981) Ullmanns Enycyklopädie der technischen Chemie, p. 299. , 4th ed., Vol, Verlag Chemie, Weinheim; Miyazaki, M., Mori, K., Nakada, K., Murakami, K., (2009), World Patent WO 2009066658Sakamoto, R., Hiroi, Y., Ishida, T., Endo, T., (2009), World Patent WO 2009057458Zhang, Y., Connely, P.R., Johnston, S., (2009), World Patent WO 2009032198Li, Z., (2009) Chinese Patent CN 101419403; Uehara, M., Yamazaki, A., Shimura, K., (1983), European Patent EP 0083971(2009) Organikum, p. 396. , Wiley-VCH, Weinheim; Lindahl, H.A., Harvey, H., (1960), US Patent 2 927 128Kreher, U.P., (2004) Molecules, 9, p. 387; Hunter, B.A., Glen, H.D., (1953), US Patent 2 635 124Bhatt, A.I., (2006) Green Chem, 8, p. 161; Zhang, J., (2005) Electrochem. Commun, 5, p. 1285; (1997), no authors named, World Patent WO 9706134Theodoropulos, S., (1983), US Patent 4 379 928Thalman, F., Kunde, E., (1995), German Patent DE 4432540Dunkel, S., Hess, U., (1997) J. Prakt. Chem, 339, p. 414; Kreher, U.P., (2003) Org. Lett, 5, p. 3107; Sridhar, G.